{{see|facade}}
==English==

===Etymology===
{{F.}} ''[[façade#French|façade]]'', from {{It.}} ''[[facciata]]'', a derivation of ''[[faccia]]'', front, from {{L.}} ''[[facies]]'', face; compare '''[[face]]'''

===Alternative spellings===
*[[facade]]

===Noun===
'''façade''' (''plural:'' '''façades''')

# {{italbrac-colon|Architecture}} The face of a building, especially the front view or [[elevation]].
#* '''1865:''' In Egypt the '''façades''' of their rock-cut tombs were ... ornamented so simply and unobtrusively as rather to belie than to announce their internal magnificence. - [[w:James Fergusson|James Fergusson]], ''A History of Architecture in All Countries'' 
#* '''1880:''' Like so many of the finest churches, [the cathedral of Siena] was furnished with a plain substantial front wall, intended to serve as the backing and support of an ornamental '''façade''' - [[w:Charles Eliot Norton|Charles Eliot Norton]], ''Historical Studies of Church-Building in the Middle Ages''
# A [[deceptive]] outward appearance.
# {{italbrac-colon|Organ building}} the [[prospect]]

